<h2 style="font-family: 'Roboto', sans-serif;">What are the Ultra Short Period Exoplanets?</h2>

<p>Ultra-short period exoplanets are a unique class of exoplanets with orbital periods less than one day. These planets
    are characterized by their extremely close proximity to their host stars, which results in intense stellar radiation
    and high surface temperatures. Often found orbiting small, less luminous stars, these planets challenge traditional
    theories about planet formation and migration, as their existence and stability so close to their stars pose
    intriguing questions for astronomers. The study of ultra-short period exoplanets offers valuable insights into the
    dynamics of planetary systems and the effects of intense stellar proximity on planetary atmospheres.</p>
